{{Reflist|group="note"|30em|refs=
<ref group="note" name="popupblock">A more complete list of Pop-Up blockers and addons / programs are in the following article [[List of pop-up blocking software]].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="PageZooming">Page zooming is different from text resizing, as it resizes not only characters, but also multimedia objects and web page layout</ref>
<ref group="note" name="EpiphanyAdBlock">Epiphany supports [[AdBlock]] as an official extension, in the [[epiphany-extensions]] package.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="FilterINI">Opera 9 introduced a content blocker for webpages ({{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060209045028/http://labs.opera.com/news/2006/02/07/2/ |date=9 February 2006 }}). Earlier releases support [[Wildcard character|wildcard]] [[Protocol (computing)|protocol]]/domain/path and filetype blocking using a filter.ini file. ({{cite web |url=http://www.schrode.net/opera/url_filtering/ |title=Opera browser: Blocking unwanted ads and other cr*p using URL filtering |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130112054413/http://www.schrode.net/opera/url_filtering/ |archivedate=12 January 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2017 |df=dmy-all }}) More advanced Ad filtering for Opera can also be done with external software.</ref>
<-- ! deleted link to an unrelated commercial website -->
<ref group="note" name="QupNonBlock">Requires building with "NONBLOCK_JS_DIALOGS" compile flag enabled; may cause crashes: https://github.com/QupZilla/qupzilla/blob/master/BUILDING{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="AdBlock">Most [[Gecko (layout engine)|Gecko]] browsers have options to block chosen images and cookies. Extended Ad filter support can be added by installing an extension such as [[Adblock Plus]].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="AdSweep">Ad filter support can be added by installing an extension such as AdSweep, AdThwart or Adblock Plus.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="GoogleChromeUpdate">Feature was intentionally removed via regular patch update, due to poor impact on performance.</ref>{{cite web|url=https://productforums.google.com/forum/#!msg/chrome/1uK-7tWOe_o/G9Q12DahJRAJ |title=Chrome full text history search |publisher=Google Chrome Help Forum |date=24 September 2013 |accessdate=5 September 2017}}
<ref group="note" name="SafariPopupBlock">Does not allow selective blocking of pop-ups. Safari can only block all pop-ups, or none.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="SafariAdblocking">Ad filter support can be added by installing extensions.{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080701200839/http://pimpmysafari.com/plugins/?c=Adblocking |date=1 July 2008 }}</ref>
<ref group="note" name="IE6Tab">IE6 had no ''tabbed browsing'' support.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="IE6Popup">IE6 included pop-up blocking with Windows XP Service Pack 2 [http://www.microsoft.com/WindowsXP/using/web/sp2_popupblocker.mspx]</ref>
<ref group="note" name="iPhoneZoom">Page zooming supported in the iPhone version of Safari. Screen zooming is built into [[macOS]].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="Spotlight">Full-text history search is available through [[Spotlight (software)|Spotlight]], a feature of the macOS operating system.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="Mozilla Developer Network - Using tab-modal prompts">{{cite web|url=https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Using_tab-modal_prompts |title=Mozilla Developer Network - Using tab-modal prompts |publisher=Developer.mozilla.org |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>
<ref group="note" name="Firefox Content-modal dialogs">{{cite web|url=https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=59314 |title=Bug 59314 - JavaScript alerts should be content-modal, not window-modal |publisher=Bugzilla.mozilla.org |date= |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>
<ref group="note" name="ChromePopup">The option "Do not allow any site to show pop-ups" in Google Chrome, which is the default, actually allows sites to show pop-ups which are not considered harmful.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="text-modal-dialogs">Although text browsers don't have dialog windows, their prompts behave as modal dialogs – block the input until answer is received.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="external">This functionality is handled by third-party software by browser's design.</ref>
