{{Reflist|group="note"|30em|refs=
<ref group="note" name="MacCaret">On macOS systems, caret navigation (called "Full Keyboard Access") can be enabled systemwide.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="MacGestures">On [[Macintosh|Mac]] systems, gestures are available systemwide via multitouch sensing on trackpads and mice.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="MacSpeech">On macOS, text-to speech and speech recognition are available systemwide and is available from menu in native Cocoa browsers.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="ELinksSpatial">ELinks 0.12 supports spatial navigation.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="EpiphanyGestures">Web supports mouse gestures as an extension from the [[Epiphany-extensions|official extensions package]].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="KonqGestures">Mouse gesture support is available system-wide in [[KDE]]</ref>
<ref group="note" name="KonqSpeech">Text-to speech support depends on the kttsd application in the kdeaccessibility package</ref>
<ref group="note" name="IEGestures">Mouse gesture support is available via plug-ins, i.e. [http://www.ysgyfarnog.co.uk/utilities/mousegestures/ Mouse Gestures for Internet Explorer] or [http://www.browsertools.net/Easy-Go-Back/ Easy Go Back].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="Minimo">[[Doug Turner (Mozilla)|Doug Turner]], the [[Minimo]] lead developer, has introduced spatial navigation to some special Firefox builds {{cite web |url=http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/asa/archives/007992.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-04-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050422043554/http://weblogs.mozillazine.org/asa/archives/007992.html |archivedate=22 April 2005 |df=dmy-all }}. It may build as a default part of Firefox {{cite web |url=https://www.mozilla.org/access/keyboard/snav/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-04-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050422001621/http://www.mozilla.org/access/keyboard/snav/ |archivedate=22 April 2005 |df=dmy-all }}.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="MozGestures">Mouse gesture support can be added by installing extensions like All-in-One Gestures (Firefox-only) [http://marc.boullet.pagesperso-orange.fr/ext/extensions-en.html] and Mouse Gestures [http://optimoz.mozdev.org/gestures/index.html].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="JAWS">Firefox works with a number of screen readers such as [[JAWS (screen reader)]] and [[Microsoft Speech API]] through extensions.{{which |date=March 2012}}</ref>
<ref group="note" name="IE8Caret">[[Internet Explorer 8]] supports caret browsing.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="SAPITTS">[[Text-to-Speech|TTS]] in Internet Explorer is available through the operating system [[Speech Application Programming Interface|Speech API]]. For TTS, SAPI takes text as input and uses the TTS engine to output that text as spoken audio. This is the same technology used by the Windows accessibility tool, Narrator. SAPI and an English TTS engine have been embedded in all Windows operating systems since the release of Windows XP.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="WSR">Internet Explorer can be controlled by applications which use the operating system [[Speech Application Programming Interface|Speech API]]. A built-in application called [[Windows Speech Recognition]] ships with [[Windows Vista]] and later client versions.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="OperaCaret">{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101004015/http://my.opera.com/shoust/blog/show.dml/305626 |date=1 November 2006 |title=opera : a sort of caret navigation can be enabled by a button or a shortcut }}</ref>
<ref group="note" name="ChromeGestures">Google Chrome can be given these features using extensions like smooth gestures, speechify and voice control for google chrome.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="QupGestures">Available as a Mouse Gestures plugin which is disabled by default, but it is part of default installation.</ref>
<ref group="note" name="QupBookm">Supports as of v1.7.0: https://github.com/QupZilla/qupzilla/issues/458</ref>
<ref group="note" name="QupSpatial">Available as of [https://github.com/QupZilla/qupzilla/commit/aac0956a0fedf19bab861963c570409bb2bd98dc this commit].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="GesturesSuite">Mouse gesture support can be added by installing extensions like Mouse Gestures Suite (Seamonkey-only) [https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/seamonkey/addon/mouse-gestures-suite/].</ref>
<ref group="note" name="FontSmoothing">Font smoothing or [[font rasterization]] is arguably an accessibility feature affecting how the fonts are rendered and font readability. Also referred as [[ClearType]] or [[TrueType]]</ref>
}}

==Acid scores==
{{relevance inline|date=September 2016}}
The [[Acid3|Acid]] tests are online test suites to determine aspects of standards compliance, to expose web page rendering flaws, and to rate the performance of browsers. Upon each test's release, they are designed so that no existing browser can pass without further development. In order for a browser to pass any Acid test, the '''latest public release''' of the browser (not an alpha, beta, release candidate, or other version under development or testing procedures) must meet the requirements shown below. In addition, the browser should be tested upon completion of installation, with no add-ons installed (some browsers make this easy by providing a "safe mode" option) and all the factory settings (no options have been changed from their defaults).

Acid1:
*Final rendering looks exactly like the rendering provided by the Acid tests website.
*Text can be highlighted and radio buttons can be selected.

Acid2:
*Final rendering looks exactly like the rendering provided by the Acid tests website.
*Smiley's nose turns blue when hovered over.

Acid3:
*Final rendering looks exactly like the rendering provided by the Acid tests website.
*Test does not report failed tests or abnormal delays (leftclick letter "A" to obtain a report)

