[[Category:Lists of AAR reporting marks|P]]

Most Serbian words are of native [[Slavic languages|Slavic]] lexical stock, tracing back to the [[Proto-Slavic language]]. There are many [[loanword]]s from different languages, reflecting cultural interaction throughout history. Notable loanwords were borrowed from Greek, Latin, Italian, Turkish, Hungarian, Russian, and German.

==Overview==
It is estimated that there are 900–1,200 Greek,{{sfn|Vlajić-Popović|2009|p=387}} 88–188 German,{{sfn|Alanović|2014|p=118}} and an uncertain high number of Turkish loanwords{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}} in modern Serbian.

==History==

===Proto-Slavic===
{{see also|Proto-Slavic borrowings}}
Ancient Greek words in Proto-Slavic are identified through phonetic features, some related to Greek phonetic history, others possibly Scythian-Sarmatian or Gothic mediations.{{sfn|Vlajić-Popović|2015|p=156}} Ancient Greek, non-mediated words are ''korablja'' (ark), ''koliba'' (cottage, hut), and supposedly ''trem'' (porch); [[Scythian languages|Scythian]] mediations are ''luk'' (onion), ''haluga'' (fence), ''koš'' (basket), ''talog'' (dregs), ''kurva'' (whore); supposedly [[Gothic language|Gothic]] mediations are ''crkva'' (church) and ''daska'' (plank).{{sfn|Vlajić-Popović|2015|p=157}} There exists loanwords in Proto-Slavic from non-Indo-European languages. Among Turanian ([[Ural-Altaic]]) lexemes, estimated to have been adopted between the 3rd and 7th century, surviving into modern Serbian are ''čaša'' (cup), ''knjiga'' (book), ''kovčeg'' (chest), ''krčag'' (pitcher), ''sablja'' (sabre).{{sfn|Radić|2015|p=134}} Adoptions from [[Proto-Avar|Avaric]] in the 6th–7th centuries are the titles ''[[ban (title)|ban]]'' and ''[[župan]]'', and ''[[klobuk]]'' (a type of hat).{{sfn|Radić|2015|pp=134–135}} South Slavic was also influenced by [[Bulgar language|Bulgar]] since their arrival in the eastern Balkans in the 7th century, e.g. ''beleg'' (landmark), ''beočug'' (shackle), ''bubreg'' (kidney), ''pašenog'' (co-brother-in-law), ''tojaga'' (bludgeon).{{sfn|Radić|2015|p=135}}

===Old Serbian===
The South Slavic languages were greatly influenced by Greek beginning in the [[Early Middle Ages]], through translation of [[Byzantine literature|Byzantine works]], leaving religious, philosophical and psychological terms.{{sfn|Ivić|1995}} Late medieval speech had very few loanwords, rather replacing Greek words with calques for linguistical purity.{{sfn|Ivić|1995}} German linguist [[Max Vasmer|Vasmer]] (1944) recorded 1,000 Greek words in Serbian, most of which were addressed in the Old Serbian form.{{sfn|Vlajić-Popović|2009|p=379}} Today, it is estimated that 900–1,200 Grecisms (''grecizmi'') exist in Serbian, more than 400 being in the church-religious section.{{sfn|Vlajić-Popović|2009|p=387}} In the economical section, apart from Greek, many words in Old Serbian were [[Romance languages|Romance]].{{sfn|Ivić|1995}} In mining, the majority of words were [[Germanic languages|Germanic]], arriving with [[Saxons in medieval Serbia|Saxons]].{{sfn|Ivić|1995}}

===Modern history===
The Ottoman conquest began a linguistical contact between Turkish and South Slavic; Turkish influence grew stronger after the 15th century.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}} Besides Turkish loanwords, also many Arabic (such as ''alat'', "tool", ''sat'', "time, clock") and Persian (''čarape'', "socks", ''šećer'', "sugar") words entered via Turkish, called "Orientalisms" (''orijentalizmi'').{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}} Also, many Greek words entered via Turkish.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}} Words for hitherto unknown sciences, businesses, industries, technologies and professions were brought by the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}} Christian villagers brought urban vocabulary from their travels to Islamic culture cities.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|pp=48–49}} Many Turkish loanwords are no longer considered loanwords.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=49}}

===Contemporary history===
English influence is seen in recent times, with the common suffixes ''-er'' and ''-ing''.<ref>{{harvnb|Štasni|Štrbac|2015}}, {{harvnb|Štrbac|Štasni|2014}}</ref> Examples are ''kasting'', ''ketering'', ''konsalting'', ''listing'', ''džoging'', ''šoping'', etc.{{sfn|Štrbac|Štasni|2014|p=102}} Foreign loanwords are becoming more frequent in sports terminology.{{sfn|Milić|Sokić|1998}}

==Comparison with other Serbo-Croatian variants==
The differences between Serbian and Croatian is mainly reflected in loanwords.{{sfn|Mønnesland|1973|p=197}} Bosnian has the most Turkish loanwords of all Serbo-Croatian variants.{{sfn|Nomachi|2015|p=48}}

===Purism===
 {{see also|Linguistic purism}}
Serbo-Croatian vocabulary is of mixed origin, with words borrowed from Greek, Latin, Italian, Turkish, Hungarian, and more recently Russian, Czech and German. Most loanwords have entered Serbian without resistance, while on the other hand in Croatian, [[linguistic purism]] was adopted as a policy during [[Austria-Hungary]] (against presumed [[Germanization]]) and later in Yugoslavia (against presumed Serbian domination). In Croatia, the term "Serbisms" is used for characteristically Serbian words,{{sfn|Lečić|2014}} unwanted during [[World War II in Yugoslavia|World War II]] and the [[Yugoslav wars]], many of which have been replaced by neologisms.{{sfn|Klajn|2008}}

